Our reasoning follows. When interpreting an MRD-test result to predict relapse the haematologist is essentially playing a “chess game against nature”. It’s his/her 1st move to make, declaring the MRD-test result positive or negative. In response the opponent (nature) has two possible moves, causing relapse or not. When \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{{{{{\rm{MRD}}}}}}}_{{{{{{\rm{worst}}}}}}\_{{{{{\rm{case}}}}}}}$$\end{document}MRDworst_case is larger the haematologist is more likely to later regret if he/she declares the MRD-test result negative, because more plausibly nature would play tricks on the haematologist by causing relapse.

