fn.p:
Strictly speaking, the worst possible value of true MRD is always ≈1 even when \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{{{{{\rm{MRD}}}}}}}_{{{{{{\rm{conventional}}}}}}}=0$$\end{document}MRDconventional=0. (The chance of true MRD ≈1 might be practically zero but the probability of this unlikely event is never zero.) Defining the worst-case scenario estimate as “not likely (probability ≤ 0.05) to exceed this value” is more useful for comparing MRD-test results.
